@node The History of @dfn{MDRevealer}
@chapter The History of @dfn{MDRevealer}

@dfn{MDRevealer}'s origin lies in a series of Perl scripts written by 
Robert Clifford from the Multidrug resistant organism Repository and 
Surveillance Network (MRSN) at the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research 
(WRAIR). For hospitals, manually parsing the results from identification / 
antibiotic susceptibility testing (ID/AST) machines to identify multidrug 
resistant isolates was time-consuming and error-prone. Therefore, he wrote a set
of Perl scripts to automate this process.

Unfortunately, these Perl scripts had their own shortcomings. For one, they only
ran on computers which had Perl installed; for another, they lacked a
user-friendly interface. In order to resolve these issues, Robin Clifford, while
an intern at WRAIR, re-implemented them as a Java application. He addded a
graphical user interface (GUI), localization support via GNU gettext, and
extended the functionality of the program to make it easier for users to
customize definitions of multidrug resistant and antibiotic susceptiblity.

@dfn{MDRevealer} processes files from Phoenix, Vitek2, and Microscan ID/AST
machines, and produces output in multiple formats.

@node Configuring @dfn{MDRevealer}
@chapter Configuring @dfn{MDRevealer}

Before using @dfn{MDRevealer}, you must first set up its configuration files. 
The main configuration file is located in the "data" directory of the program, 
and is called @strong{config.txt}. By default, it looks like this:

@sp 2

@example
Facility @ @ @ @ 0000
Machine name @ @ @ @ Test Machine

#If you want the program to write its output files to the same place every
#time, delete the # marks from the lines below and change the names of
#"report.txt" and so on to what you want the outputs to be called.

Default detailed report location @ @ @ @ output/report.txt
Default summary location @ @ @ @ output/summary.txt
Default spreadsheet location @ @ @ @ output/spreadsheet.txt
Default .dat location @ @ @ @ output/dat.txt
Default localized output @ @ @ @ output/localized.txt

Default MDR file @ @ @ @ data/mdr.txt
Default breakpoints file @ @ @ @ data/breakpoints.txt
Custom parser file @ @ @ @ data/parsers/my_parser.txt

.dat output
lastName @ @ @ @ firstName @ @ @ @ middleI @ @ @ @ dmisId @ @ @ @ spin @ @ @ @ 
ssnPrefix @ @ @ @ ssn @ @ @ @ dob @ @ @ @ gender @ @ @ @ accession  @ @ @ @ 
isolationDate @ @ @ @ cultureType @ @ @ @ source @ @ @ @ locationType @ @ @ @ 
location @ @ @ @ isolate @ @ @ @ organism @ @ @ @ alternateOrganism @ @ @ @ 
equipment @ @ @ @ antibiotic @ @ @ @ mic @ @ @ @ call
@end example
@sp 2

The contents of @strong{config.txt} are described in the following sections.

@section The "Facility" Field

MDRevealer looks for a line beginning with "Facility" (minus the quotes), a
tab, and the four-digit ID number of the facility the data came from. The ID 
number refers to a facility in @strong{data/hospitals.txt}. The 
@strong{hospitals.txt} file included with the program contains a list of all
US Army medical facilities. To add a new hospital, the entry for ID 
number 0000 can be edited.

@section The "Machine name" Field

MDRevealer looks for a line beginning with "Machine name" (minus the quotes), a
tab, and the name of the machine the isolates were tested on. This lets the user
specify the equipment name if it isn't provided in the input file.

@section The "Parser" Field

MDRevealer looks for a line beginning with "Parser" (minus the quotes), a tab,
and the name of a parser. Valid parsers are:


If a parser isn't uncommented in @strong{config.txt}, then MDRevealer will
display a warning and close.

@section Default Locations

Each type of MDRevealer output file has a default name and location. If 
you don't want the program to automatically write your output files to a default
location, simply delete those lines. Otherwise, change "report.txt", 
"summary.txt", "spreadsheet.txt", etc. to your preferred location.
All locations are relative to the program (MDRevealer.jar). 
For example, if you want the program to write your detailed reports to 
"report.txt" in a folder called "output", which is in the same folder as the 
program, you would do this:
@example
...
Default detailed report location @ @ @ @ output/report.txt
...
@end example

If you want it to be written to a folder called "output" in your home directory,
you would do this (on GNU/Linux, *BSD, OS X, etc.):

@example
Default detailed report location @ @ @ @ /home/[your username]/output/report.txt
@end example

Or on Windows:

@example
Default detailed report location @ @ @ @ C:/Users/[your username]/output/report.txt
@end example

Please note that the directory must be created before MDRevealer is run.

@section Default MDR Criteria and Drug Susceptibility Breakpoints

If you want to use custom antibiotic susceptibility breakpoints or MDR criteria,
just comment out the lines, and when you run the program, it'll prompt you
to give it an MDR definition file and a breakpoint file every time. To comment 
them out, change the lines to this:

@example
#Default MDR file @ @ @ @ data/mdr.txt
#Default breakpoints file @ @ @ @ data/breakpoints.txt
@end example

@section Custom parser file

This line points to the file that will be used when the user selects the
"custom parser" option in MDRevealer.

@section .dat output.

If the program finds a line in config.txt labeled ".dat output", it uses
the next line to determine which data fields should appear in the tab-delimited
.dat output file.

The fields the program recognizes are:

@itemize @bullet

@item
lastName = The last name of the patient. (Ex: SMITH)

@item
firstName = The first name of the patient. (Ex: JOHN)

@item
middleI = The middle initial of the patient. (Ex: Q)

@item
dmisId = The facility the bacterium was found at. (Ex: 9009 TEST HOSPITAL)

@item
spin = 	An identifier used by MRSN.

@item
ssnPrefix = The SSN prefix of the patient, used in the US military healthcare
system. (Ex: 20)

@item
ssn = The Social Security Number (SSN) of the patient. (Ex: 987654320)

@item
dob = The birth date of the patient. (Ex: 07/04/1776)

@item
gender = The gender of the patient. (Ex: F)

@item
accession = The accesssion number of the bacterium. (Ex: 12121)

@item
isolationDate = The date the clinical sample was taken from the patient. 
(Ex: 7/16/2013)

@item
cultureType = A general description of the tissue or fluid that the organism
was isolated from. (Ex: BLOOD)

@item
source = A more specific version of cultureType. (Ex: LEG ABSCESS)

@item
locationType = A general hospital location. (Ex: ICU)

@item
location =  A specific location within a hospital. (Ex: WARD 5)

@item
isolate = The isolate number of the bacterium. If multiple species of bacterium
are isolated from a single culture, each has the same accession, but a unique
isolate number. (Ex: 2)

@item
organism = The organism's display name from @strong{organisms.txt}. 
(Ex: E. coli)

@item
alternateOrganism = Rarely used; generally only found when "organism" is 
"other". (Ex: Shigella sonnei)

@item
longOrganism = The organism's full name. 
(Ex: Acinetobacter baumannii)

@item
equipment = The ID/AST equipment used to produce the data. (Ex: Vitek2)

@item
antibiotic = The name of the drug tested. Each drug tested will appear on a
separate row. (Ex: Amikacin)

@item
mic = The minimum inhibitory concentration. Each  MIC will appear on a separate
row. (Ex: <=1)

@item
call = Whether the organism was sensitive, resistant, or indeterminate. Each 
call will appear on a separate row. (Ex: S)

@end itemize

The user can delete or reorder these fields in config.txt as they see fit in
order to create their own customized .dat file.

@node Configuring the XML Tests
@chapter Configuring the XML Tests

MDRevealer 2.0 added support for writing your own tests for carbapenem
resistance, MRSA status, VRE status, or ESBL status. An example:

@example
<?xml version="1.0"?>
	<test>
		<test_name>PSA Carb Test</test_name>
		<bacterium>Pseudomonas</bacterium>
		<condition number = "1" default = "passed">
			<drug>
				<name>Cefepime</name>
				<if read_type = "Call" value = "S">
					<condition_status>failed</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
			<drug>
				<name>Cefotaxime</name>
				<if read_type = "Call" value = "S">
					<condition_status>failed</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
			<drug>
				<name>Ceftazidime</name>
				<if read_type = "Call" value = "S">
					<condition_status>failed</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
			<drug>
				<name>Ceftriaxone</name>
				<if read_type = "Call" value = "S">
					<condition_status>failed</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
			<drug>
				<name>Ertapenem</name>
				<if read_type = "Call" value = "S">
					<condition_status>failed</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
		</condition>
		<condition number = "2" default = "failed" number_required = "1">
			<drug>
				<name>Doripenem</name>
				<if read_type = "MIC" comparison="greater_than_equal" value = "4">
					<condition_status>+</condition_status>
				</if>
				<name>Imipenem</name>
				<if read_type = "MIC" comparison="greater_than_equal" value = "4">
					<condition_status>+</condition_status>
				</if>
				<name>Meropenem</name>
				<if read_type = "MIC" comparison="greater_than_equal" value = "4">
					<condition_status>+</condition_status>
				</if>
			</drug>
		</condition>
		<required_condition>1</required_condition>
		<required_condition>2</required_condition>
		<result>Carb</result>
	</test>
@end example

In English, this works out to...

@example
Test all bacteria with Pseudomonas in their name.
Condition #1 is met by default, and must be failed.
If the call of Cefepime is S, fail the condition.
If the call of Cefotaxime is S, fail the condition.
If the call of Ceftazidime is S, fail the condition.
If the call of Ceftriaxone is S, fail the condition.
If the call of Ertapenem is S, fail the condition.
Condition #2 is failed by default, and must be met.
If one sub-condition is true, the condition is met.
If the MIC of Doripenem is >=4, the sub-condition is met.
If the MIC of Imipenem is >=4, the sub-condition is met.
If the MIC of Meropenem is >=4, the sub-condition is met.
Condition 1 must be met.
Condition 2 must be met.
If the above conditions are met, the bacterium is carbapenem resistant.
@end example

Here's a list of tags MDRevealer will recognize.

@itemize @bullet

@item
<test>: Defines a test.

@item
<test_name>: Defines the name of the test. It gets printed to stdout when
the program executes the test.

@item
<bacterium>: The name of the bacterium to run tests against. The program
will look for any bacteria containing this name: 
<bacterium>Klebsiella</bacterium> will result in the program running its
tests against any bacterium with "Klebsiella" in its name.
Setting the name to "Generic" will have it run tests on any bacteria
whose name is not found in "carbapenem.txt".
Setting the name to "Any" will have it run tests on all bacteria.

@item
<condition>: Defines a condition.


@itemize 
Attributes:

@item
number: The number of the condition, used for identifying it.

@item
default: Must be either "passed" or "failed". It determines if the test
is considered to be passed or failed by default.

@item
number_required: The number of sub-conditions that must be passed to consider
the condition passed.

For example:

@example

For condition 2: one or more of Doripenem, Imipenem, and Meropnem must
have a MIC >=4.

In this case, Doripenem's MIC being >=4 would be a sub-condition.

@end example

@end itemize

@item
<drug>: Defines a drug.

@item
<name>: Defines the name of a drug.

@item
<if>: If the conditions in its attributes are met, the program does whatever
<condition_status> says to do.

@itemize 
Attributes:

@item
read_type: The type of read to look at: call or MIC.

@item
comparison: Must be either "less_than_equal" (<=), "less_than" (<),
"greater_than_equal" (>=), or "greater_than" (>).

@item
value: What value to compare the read_type to.

@end itemize

@item
<condition_status>: What to do if <if> is met.

@itemize 
@item
failed: Fail the condition.

@item
passed: Pass the condition.

@item
+: Pass the sub-condition.

@item
-: Fail the sub-condition.

@end itemize

@item
<required_condition>: This condition must be met to pass the test.


@item
<required_if>: This condition must be met to pass the test, but only
if the requirements in its attributes are met.

An example:

@example
		<required_if drug="Ertapenem" read_type="MIC" comparison="greater_than_equal" value="1">1</required_if>
		<required_if drug="Ertapenem" read_type="MIC" comparison="less_than_equal" value="0">2</required_if>
		<required_if drug="Ertapenem" read_type="MIC" comparison="less_than_equal" value="0.5">3</required_if>
@end example

And in English:

@example
If the MIC of Ertapenem is >=1, condition 1 must be met.
If the MIC of Ertapenem is <=0, condition 2 must be met.
If the MIC of Ertapenem is <=0.5, condition 3 must be met.
@end example

Attributes are the same as the ones for <if>.


@item
<result>: What to do if the test is passed.

@itemize 

@item
Carb: Mark the isolate as carbapenem resistant.

@item
MRSA: Mark the isolate as MRSA.

@item
ESBL: Mark the isolate as ESBL.

@item
VRE: Mark the isolate as VRE.

@item
Anything else: Mark the isolate as whatever you put between the tags.

@end itemize
@end itemize

