@node Other Configuration Files
@chapter Other Configuration Files

Each data file used by MDRevealer has one or more fields, each
separated by a tab.

@section breakpoints.txt

This file is used to provide customized susceptibility breakpoints that will
replace the susceptibility calls made by an ID/AST machine.

A line in breakpoints.txt looks like this:

@example
ACB @ @ @ @ Amikacin @ @ @ @ 16 @ @ @ @ 64
@end example

The first column is the name of the organism.

The second column is the name of the drug you're testing against the organism.

If the MIC of the drug is less than or equal to the value in the third column,
the program will call it sensitive (S).

If the MIC of the drug is greater than or equal to the value in the fourth
column, the program will call it resistant (R).

If the MIC of the drug is in between the two values, the program will call it
indeterminate (I).

If a breakpoints file is selected, and the input file contains an organism/drug
combination absent from @strong{mdr.txt}, the program will write a warning and 
set the call to "X".

@section carbapenem.txt

A line in carbapenem.txt looks like this:

@example
ACB
@end example

Any organism whose name is found in this file will be excluded from the generic
carbapenem test.

All names in carbapenem.txt must be in ALL CAPS.

@section drugnames.txt

A line in drugnames.txt looks like this:

@example
amikacin @ @ @ @ Amikacin
@end example

The first column is the synonym for a drug.

The second column is the preferred drug name.

This file helps prevent confusion due to alternate names for drugs, or
simple misspellings. To avoid false positives in warnings.txt, the proper name
must also be in the file, like so:

@example
Amikacin @ @ @ @ Amikacin
@end example

@section hospitals.txt

A line in hospitals.txt looks like this:

@example
0001 @ @ @ @ FOX AHC-REDSTONE ARSENAL
@end example

The first column is the facility's ID number. The program
uses this field for creating the SPIN, an identifier for each bacterium used by
MRSN.

The second column is the name of the facility.

@section mdr.txt

A line in mdr.txt looks like this:

@example
ACB @ @ @ @ A @ @ @ @ Cefepime
@end example

The first column is the organism's name.

The second column is the category of the drug.
Each drug is assigned to an antibiotic category, such as beta-lactams,
aminoglycosides, fluoroquinolones, etc.
Each category should be marked with a letter: A through O. You shouldn't
need more than 15 categories, but if you do, email me. @xref{Contact}.

The last column is the organism's name.


@section organisms.txt

A line in organisms.txt looks like this:

@example
ACINETOBACTER LOWFFI @ @ @ @ Acinetobacter lwoffii @ @ @ @ A. lwoffii @ @ @ @ 834683456
@end example

The first column is a common name. This name must be in ALL CAPS.

The second name is used internally by the program. It must be genus and species.

The last name is the display name used in the output files. It can be whatever 
the user wants, but by default, it's the first letter of the genus, a dot, 
a space, and the species.

The number at the end is the organism's SNOMED code. Currently the program 
doesn't use this for anything, but it might at some point. This is optional, so
feel free to leave it off.

