@node Using @dfn{MDRevealer}
@chapter Using @dfn{MDRevealer}

Before running the program, make sure that every organism name in your input
file is in organisms.txt, and if not, add it. Otherwise, you won't get
the right results.

Once you've got the program configured, it's time to actually run it. A brief
explanation of each option follows.

@itemize @bullet

@item
Detailed report (in English) - Prints out a detailed list of all drugs a
bacterium's resistant/sensitive to.

@item
Summary (in English) - Prints accession, isolate, organism name, and MDR status.

@item
Spreadsheet (in English) - Prints out a tab-delimited text file with one sample
per row.

@item
.dat file (in English) - Prints out a tab-delimited text file with one organism/
drug per row.

@item
Detailed report (in your current language) - Prints out a detailed report in the
OS's current language.

@item
Ignore calls from the machines and have the program calculate them - Uses
breakpoints.txt to determine sensitive/resistant/intermediate status based on
the MIC. If no information about the organism-drug combo's available in
breakpoints.txt, the program will print a warning and set the call to "X".

@end itemize

The dropdown menu allows you to select which parser you want to use.

@itemize @bullet
@item
Vitek1 - A parser for a text report from the bioMeriux VITEK2 machine 
(format 1).

@item
Phoenix1 - A parser for a text report from the BD Phoenix machine (format 1).

@item
Custom parser - A parser that reads in a custom parser file and uses it to
determine how to parse the input file.

@end itemize

Once you've selected your options, hit "OK" to continue, "Cancel" to close the
program, or "About" to see the program's license.

After hitting "OK", select your input file. After the program calculates the
necessary info, it'll either automatically write your files to the default
locations specified in @strong{config.txt}, or it'll prompt you to give it a 
place to put them.

@section Warnings

Sometimes, information that the program thinks should be in its data files
won't be there. When that happens, it'll output a warning to warnings.txt,
found in the same directory as the program. Here are examples:

@example
Warning: the organism name "Staphylococcus aureus" does not appear in
organisms.txt. Either this is a typo, or the name is missing from the file.
@sp 1
No breakpoint found for Klebsiella pneumoniae and Amikacin
@end example

When the program tells you that things are missing, add them, and shoot me
an email so that I can add them to the data files for the next
version of the program.

@section Crashes

Sometimes, the program will close unexpectedly. When this happens, here's
what to do.

@itemize @bullet

@item
Is there a "lib" folder in the same directory as MDRevealer.jar,
and does that folder have a file called "libintl.jar" in it?

@item
Are you using the right parser? Using, say, the Vitek parser on
a file from a Phoenix machine might cause unexpected behavior.

@item
If you're sure that's not the case, look in warnings.txt. At the bottom,
you should see something like:

@example
Fatal error: class java.lang.IndexOutOfBoundsException

java.util.ArrayList.rangeCheck(ArrayList.java:635)
java.util.ArrayList.get(ArrayList.java:411)
MDRevealer.Output.printOutput(Output.java:91)
MDRevealer.Parser.parse(Parser.java:403)
MDRevealer.MDRevealer$ButtonListener.actionPerformed(MDRevealer.java:188)
@end example

Send your config file, your warnings file, and an anonymized version of your
input file to me, and I'll fix whatever the problem is.

@end itemize

