@section Using gettext

To extract strings for translation, run this command in
MDRevealer/src/MDRevealer (with GNU gettext installed):

@example
xgettext -k_ --add-comments="TRANSLATORS:" -o ../../po/[lang].po MDRevealer.java
call.java mtf.java Resistances.java Output.java Parser.java Organism.java
@end example

Where [lang] is your ISO 631 language code.

So for French, you would run:

@example
xgettext -k_ --add-comments="TRANSLATORS:" -o ../../po/fr.po MDRevealer.java
call.java mtf.java Resistances.java Output.java Parser.java Organism.java
@end example

You can also run makemdrevealer.sh, and rename po/MDRevealer.po to fr.po or
whatever.

To compile the program, add this line to makemdrevealer.sh:

@example
msgfmt --java2 -d build/classes -r MDRevealer -l [lang] po/[lang].po
@end example

Again, [lang] is your ISO 631 language code.

So for French, you would add:

msgfmt --java2 -d /build/classes -r MDRevealer -l fr po/fr.po

Then run the script. @xref{Compiling}.

@node Compiling
@appendix Compiling
makemdrevealer.sh is a script to automatically compile the program, add
any .po files, generate a default .po file, compile this manual,
and package a .zip file for release, as well as another .zip with the source.

To run it, you will need:

@itemize @bullet

@item
gettext (to extract the strings)

@item
texinfo (to build the manual)

@item
zip (to make the zips)

@item
apache-ant (to compile)

@item
java-environment (to compile... and to run the program, obviously!)

@end itemize

Note that these package names only apply to Parabola GNU/Linux
and other Arch Linux forks (as well as Arch itself).
Other Unix-like operating systems may use different names for them.

If you're on a Unix-like system (GNU/Linux, *BSD, OS X, etc.), just run this
from a shell: ./makemdrevealer.sh.
If you're on Windows, as RMS says, "Either throw Windows out of your computer
or throw your computer out the window" ;)@sp 1
If you aren't willing to do that, just download Cygwin and run
./makemdrevealer.sh.

Before running it, be sure to set "version" and "revision" to the current
version and revision numbers, respectively!

Also note that the script will overwrite data/config.txt with defaultconfig.txt.
To prevent this, place a # in front of:
@example
cp -f defaultconfig.txt data/config.txt
@end example

